{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: Power vs. Energy Measurement",
    "objective": "Synthesize the difference between measuring the rate of work and total consumption by identifying the correct instruments for each in a practical scenario.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In professional electrical science, we must distinguish between the 'rate' of doing work and the 'total' work done over time.",
      "A common site requirement is to monitor both the instantaneous demand of a machine to ensure it isn't overloaded and the cumulative usage for billing or energy management.",
      "Selecting the correct instrument depends entirely on whether you are looking at a single moment in time or a duration of hours or days."
    ],
    "questionText": "A factory manager needs to monitor a large extractor fan. They require a measurement of the 'rate' at which the fan is currently using electricity to check for motor strain, and a separate measurement of the 'total' electricity consumed by the fan over a 24-hour shift for cost analysis. Identify the two specific instruments required for these tasks and explain the functional difference between what they are measuring.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Wattmeter used to measure Power (the instantaneous rate of work/demand).",
      "Energy Meter (or Kilowatt-hour meter) used to measure Energy (the total consumption over time).",
      "The functional difference is that Power is a snapshot of the current 'work rate', whereas Energy is the cumulative total of that power used over a specific duration."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which meter gives you a 'live' reading of demand and which one acts like a counter that adds up usage over time."
  }
}

